This is a simplified excerpt of our task structure.

```python
class AnalysisTask(Task):

	localRoot = Parameter("/user/public")
	campaign  = Parameter(default="analysisFiles")
	setup     = Parameter(default="RunIIFall15")
	dataset   = Parameter(default="ttJets")
	lepton    = Parameter(default="mu")
	shift     = Parameter(default="nominal")
	postfix   = Parameter() # required
	
	@property
	def analysisId(self):
		return (self.campaign, self.setup, self.dataset,
		        self.lepton, self.shift, self.postfix)


class GridTask(Task):

	gridTaskName = Parameter() # required
	
	@property
	def gridWorkArea(self):
		return os.path.join(os.getcwd(), "grid_tasks")
	
	@property
	def gridTaskDir(self):
	    return os.path.join(self.gridWorkArea, self.gridTaskName)


class GridAnalysisTask(GridTask, AnalysisTask):

	# here I want to override gridTaskName to always be something
	# like "gridTaskName = '_'.join(self.analysisId)"
	gridTaskName = Parameter(default=None, description="ignored, set automatically")

	@property
	def gridWorkArea(self):
		return os.path.join(self.localRoot, "grid_tasks")


class GridSubmitTask(GridTask):
	...


class GridStatusTask(GridTask):
	...


class GridAnalysisSubmitTask(GridAnalysisTask, GridSubmitTask):
	...
```


The important part is where I want to override ``gridTaskName`` in the ``GridAnalysisTask`` class. With the hook method proposed in the PR I would simply do:

```python

class GridAnalysisTask(GridTask, AnalysisTask):

	gridTaskName = Parameter(default=None, description="ignored, set automatically")
	
	@classmethod
	def param_hook(cls, result, args, kwargs):
		keys = ("campaign", "setup", "dataset", "lepton", "shift", "postfix")
		result["gridTaskName"] = "_".join(result[key] for key in keys)
	
	...
```

I want to point out that most tasks, e.g. ``AnalysisTask`` or ``GridTask`` are inherited by other tasks as well, so I cannot merge them (as this example would suggest) and we benefit a lot from the inheritance structure.

